United Kingdom":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1245–":"1245–Afdød","1245–Male":"1245–Afdød","1255–Female":"1255–Afdød","1269–Male":"1269–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","abt.  1269":"omkring 1269","Stopham, Sussex, England":"Stopham, Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1245–":"1245–Overleden","1245–Male":"1245–Overleden","1255–Female":"1255–Overleden","1269–Male":"1269–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","abt.  1269":"circa 1269","Stopham, Sussex, England":"Stopham, Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1245–":"1245–Deceased","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","1269–Male":"1269–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","abt.  1269":"about 1269","Stopham, Sussex, England":"Stopham, Sussex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"atte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Cecile, Gervais, Jean Pierre, Jean-Claude, Leonce, Pierre.","South German: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow, from Middle High German <i>matte</i> ‘meadow’.","German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> or <i>Matthäus</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Matter","meanings":["German: topographic name for someone who lived by a meadow, from   Matte   1 + <i>-er</i>, suffix denoting an inhabitant.","English (Lancashire); Dutch (also <b>De Matter</b>): occupational name for a maker of mats, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>matte</i>, Middle Dutch <i>mat</i> ‘mat’."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]}]},{"name":"Forde","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan, Dermot, Aine, Fionnuala, Liam, Nuala.","English and Irish: variant of   Ford   1 and 2. This is a very common spelling in Ireland.","Norwegian (<b>Førde</b>): habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Førde (there are eleven on the west coast), from Old Norse <i>fyrthi</i>, dative of <i>fjǫrthr</i> ‘fjord’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ford","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived near a ford (Middle English, Old English <i>ford</i>), or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, such as Ford (Durham, Herefordshire, Northumberland, Shropshire, Sussex), Ford in Sefton (Lancashire), Ford in Crediton and Ford in Holcombe Rogus (both Devon), Ford in Litton and Ford in Wiveliscombe (both Somerset).","Irish: Anglicized form (quasi-translation) of various Gaelic names, for example <b>MacGiolla na Naomh</b> ‘son of <i>Gilla na Naomh</i>’ (a personal name meaning ‘servant of the saints’), <b>Mac Conshámha</b> ‘son of <i>Conshnámha</i>’ (a personal name composed of the elements <i>con</i> ‘dog’ + <i>snámh</i> ‘to swim’), in all of which the final syllable was wrongly thought to be <i>áth</i> ‘ford’, and <b>Ó Fuar(th)áin</b> (see   Foran  ).","Americanized form of French   Faure   ‘blacksmith’."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Peter atte Forde was born in 1245, in England, United Kingdom as the son of Forde. He married Mrs Peter atte Forde about 1269, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1245–":"1245–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1269–Male":"1269–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","abt.  1269":"umbes 1269","Stopham, Sussex, England":"Stopham, Sussex, England","E